1
00:00:03,720 --> 00:00:07,420
In order to choose an appropriate plot for your data,

2
00:00:07,420 --> 00:00:10,180
you need to understand the types of the data you have.

3
00:00:10,180 --> 00:00:14,350
One common method divides data into four data types: nominal,

4
00:00:14,350 --> 00:00:17,575
ordinal, interval, and ratio.

5
00:00:17,575 --> 00:00:21,070
The first two are known as qualitative or categorical types,

6
00:00:21,070 --> 00:00:25,330
while the last two are known as quantitative or numeric types.

7
00:00:25,330 --> 00:00:32,725
Furthermore, quantitative types include a second classification, discrete or continuous.

8
00:00:32,725 --> 00:00:38,380
Features that are categorical are those that act as non-numeric labels on the data.

9
00:00:38,380 --> 00:00:42,690
Nominal data are pure labels without any natural ordering.

10
00:00:42,690 --> 00:00:47,555
Examples of this include things like movie genre or country.

11
00:00:47,555 --> 00:00:50,660
Ordinal variables are also labels,

12
00:00:50,660 --> 00:00:52,340
but unlike nominal variables,

13
00:00:52,340 --> 00:00:54,845
these include an intrinsic ordering.

14
00:00:54,845 --> 00:00:58,280
Examples of this type of variable include letter grade on

15
00:00:58,280 --> 00:01:01,985
a test or ranking at the end of a competition.

16
00:01:01,985 --> 00:01:06,005
While categorical variables might be recorded numerically,

17
00:01:06,005 --> 00:01:10,265
you should not make the mistake of performing numeric operations with them.

18
00:01:10,265 --> 00:01:12,890
For example, let's say that the rankings

19
00:01:12,890 --> 00:01:16,165
above come from a list of the best books of the year.

20
00:01:16,165 --> 00:01:18,750
You wouldn't expect the goodness of

21
00:01:18,750 --> 00:01:22,945
the first and second place books combined to equal that of the third place book.

22
00:01:22,945 --> 00:01:27,400
Or that the second and third place books sum up to the first place book.

23
00:01:27,400 --> 00:01:30,590
You can only say that first place is better than

24
00:01:30,590 --> 00:01:33,635
second place and second place is better than third,

25
00:01:33,635 --> 00:01:35,635
but not by how much.

26
00:01:35,635 --> 00:01:39,290
Knowing the difference between first and second doesn't necessarily

27
00:01:39,290 --> 00:01:43,255
tell you that the difference between second and third will be the same.

28
00:01:43,255 --> 00:01:45,830
Quantitative data on the other hand,

29
00:01:45,830 --> 00:01:49,700
take numerical values that allow for mathematical operations.

30
00:01:49,700 --> 00:01:54,485
For interval-type data, differences between numeric values are meaningful.

31
00:01:54,485 --> 00:01:59,840
Examples of this type of variable include year or temperature in Celsius.

32
00:01:59,840 --> 00:02:02,990
An increase or decrease of one point will

33
00:02:02,990 --> 00:02:06,640
mean the same thing no matter where you are on each scale.

34
00:02:06,640 --> 00:02:10,430
Ratio type data also allows for different comparisons,

35
00:02:10,430 --> 00:02:13,085
but also require an additional property.

36
00:02:13,085 --> 00:02:15,820
For a variable to be considered ratio type,

37
00:02:15,820 --> 00:02:20,510
there must be a meaningful zero point such that ratio judgments are meaningful.

38
00:02:20,510 --> 00:02:24,484
Consider the earlier example regarding temperature in Celsius.

39
00:02:24,484 --> 00:02:26,495
Since temperature is interval,

40
00:02:26,495 --> 00:02:28,310
the difference between five degrees and

41
00:02:28,310 --> 00:02:32,255
10 degrees is the same as that between 10 and 15 degrees.

42
00:02:32,255 --> 00:02:35,345
But Celsius is not a ratio-type variable.

43
00:02:35,345 --> 00:02:39,005
You wouldn't say that 10 degrees is twice as hot as five degrees,

44
00:02:39,005 --> 00:02:42,090
or 15 degrees three times as hot as five.

45
00:02:42,090 --> 00:02:46,070
Examples of ratio type data include the length of a document

46
00:02:46,070 --> 00:02:50,150
by word count or measurement of mass in kilograms.

47
00:02:50,150 --> 00:02:54,305
All quantitative variables, whether interval or ratio type,

48
00:02:54,305 --> 00:02:58,190
can also be classified as discrete or continuous.

49
00:02:58,190 --> 00:03:02,300
Discrete quantitative variables can only take on specific values,

50
00:03:02,300 --> 00:03:05,690
while continuous variables can take on any value.

51
00:03:05,690 --> 00:03:09,620
Year and word count are examples of discrete variables.

52
00:03:09,620 --> 00:03:12,320
They can only take on integer values.

53
00:03:12,320 --> 00:03:16,775
Temperature and mass are examples of continuous variables.

54
00:03:16,775 --> 00:03:20,540
These variables can take on any number of decimal values if we

55
00:03:20,540 --> 00:03:24,900
had instruments capable of recording them with that precision.

